Okay.  It's obvious that the noise channel being a white noise channel is full of sh.  The noise channel, when I view the wave looks like a square wave with patterned randomized pulse widths.<br /><br />I looked at wikipedia's refference of how it works:<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_feedback_shift_register">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_fee ... t_register</a><!-- m --><br /><br />It makes a lot of sense now when I saw that, so tell me if I'm right when I discribe it.<br /><br />The noise channel has a register that discribes the shape of the wave.<br />The binary is the amplitude, so it would look like this:<br /><br />examples<br /><br />1 0 1 0<br />_ ¯ _ ¯ <br /><br />1 1 0 1<br />_ _ ¯ _ <br /><br />And there are multiple bits put into a pattern.  The 2 modes in the noise channel are switches between the 2 patterns that NES has.<br /><br />The pitch describes how fast it cycles through the pattern.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3046">CKY-2K/Clay Man</a> — Thu Feb 07, 2008 12:32 pm</p><hr />
